# __PROJECT_NAME__

Minimal verified Python Google Chat application generated by
`googlechatai@__GOOGLECHATAI_VERSION__`.

## First local success

```bash
python3 -m venv .venv
.venv/bin/python -m pip install -r requirements.txt
.venv/bin/python -m unittest
npx googlechatai@__GOOGLECHATAI_VERSION__ inspect fixtures/mention.json
npx googlechatai@__GOOGLECHATAI_VERSION__ card lint fixtures/card.json
npx googlechatai@__GOOGLECHATAI_VERSION__ replay fixtures/mention.json \
  --language python \
  --python .venv/bin/python \
  --handler app.py \
  --expect-text "You said"
npx googlechatai@__GOOGLECHATAI_VERSION__ doctor
```

The fixture and test are sanitized and require no Google account, credentials,
or network access.

## Configure a live callback

1. Copy `.env.example` to `.env.local` or set the values in your deployment.
2. Set the numeric `GOOGLE_CHAT_PROJECT_NUMBER`.
3. Set `GOOGLE_CHAT_APP_USER` to the app's `users/...` resource.
4. Deploy `server.py` and configure its `/chat/events` URL in Google Cloud.
5. Set `GOOGLE_CHAT_ENDPOINT_CONFIGURED=1` after verifying that exact URL.
6. Copy `smoke-space.example.json` to the ignored
   `smoke-space.local.json`, then replace its resource placeholders with a
   dedicated space containing no real users.
7. Run `npx googlechatai@__GOOGLECHATAI_VERSION__ doctor`.

`server.py` refuses to start without an audience and verifies every callback
before dispatch. Google Cloud project creation, Chat registration, OAuth
consent, administrator approval, and deployment remain explicit operator
steps.

Run the configured server:

```bash
set -a
. ./.env.local
set +a
.venv/bin/python server.py
```

Before any write, inspect the guarded smoke plan:

```bash
npx googlechatai@__GOOGLECHATAI_VERSION__ smoke \
  --metadata smoke-space.local.json
```

Live smoke needs a short-lived user OAuth token with Chat space-read and
message-read/write access, plus an installed app. Keep the token out of
`.env.local` and shell history. The CLI additionally requires
`RUN_LIVE_GOOGLECHATAI_SMOKE=1` and `--live`; it verifies the dedicated space,
sends one mention, checks that the app replies in the triggering thread, and
deletes the prompt.
